## Novelty ranking (most to least novel)

1. **Quantified persistence + cross-cohort-validated silencing memory** — methylation memory that survives therapy, validated out-of-cohort (p=2.6e-86). Candidate substrate for same-site relapse.
2. **Predictability of epigenetic permanence (deep ML, AUROC 0.82)** — first model of *which* psoriatic epigenetic changes become permanent + their molecular determinants.
3. **GATA-motif / CpG-island differentiation-enhancer localization** — sequence-confirmed regulatory drivers of the scar (GATA triple-confirmed).
4. **Cross-cohort scar biomarker (AUROC 0.84)** — the scar as a transferable diagnostic methylation signature.
5. **Epigenetic instability + patient scar-load heterogeneity** — the scar loci are destabilized and define a scar-high/low patient axis.
6. **Enhancer-methylation independently tracks silencing** — quantitative integration beyond promoters.

## Clinical-utility ranking

1. **Diagnostic biomarker** — scar methylation classifies psoriasis cross-cohort (0.84); deployable on standard 450K arrays.
2. **Relapse-risk hypothesis** — the persistent silencing memory is a candidate molecular substrate for same-site recurrence (testable with longitudinal relapse cohorts).
3. **Patient stratification** — scar-load axis may index epigenetic-burden subtypes.
4. **Negative for response-prediction** — baseline transcriptome does NOT predict ustekinumab response (saves a blind alley).

## Honest limitations

- Methylation and expression are cross-modality (different samples); gene-level integration, not per-patient multi-omics.
- The activation/hypomethylation memory does not replicate cross-cohort (down-weighted).
- Persistence is whole-methylome, not scar-specific; the scar is the interpretable subset.
- No relapse-outcome data — the relapse link is a hypothesis, not demonstrated.
- The differentiation-silencing target is shared with atopic dermatitis; psoriasis-specificity rests on persistence, untestable cross-disease (no AD methylation).


## Addendum — confirmatory & keystone experiments (added after master table)

| Experiment | Result | Verdict |
|---|---|---|
| Random-effects meta-analysis | all 16 silencing genes significant; GATA3 pooled g=-2.21 (p=2e-16) across 11 cohorts | POSITIVE (journal-grade) |
| Single-cell rigor (composition) | 9/10 memory genes silenced WITHIN keratinocytes (per-cell) | CONFOUND RULED OUT |
| Keystone dissociation | expression recovers ~72% on ustekinumab; 72% methylation persists | POSITIVE (relapse model) |
| Treatment-class generality | etanercept +0.30 / ustekinumab +0.28 log2 re-activation (GSE106992) | POSITIVE (class-general) |

**These four hardened the core:** the GATA-driven silencing is statistically robust across 11 cohorts (meta-analysis), keratinocyte-intrinsic (single-cell, composition ruled out), recovers transcriptionally under two biologic classes while the methylation scar persists (keystone) -- the mechanistic basis of the primed-memory relapse model.


## Addendum 2 — relapse-model & specificity experiments

| Experiment | Result | Verdict |
|---|---|---|
| Basal-compartment memory | silencing present in basal/progenitor keratinocytes (5/10) | relapse-competent (heritable compartment) |
| Field effect (nonlesional) | 6/12 dev-TFs partially silenced in nonlesional (~13%) | mild predisposition, lesion-driven bulk |
| Transcriptional treatment-resistance | residual is IMMUNE (CD8A/CCL5, IFN-g); overlaps methylation memory by 1 gene | decoupled axes (silent epigenetic scar) |

**Relapse-model support:** the silencing memory sits in the long-lived basal compartment (heritable), nonlesional skin carries a mild developmental-TF predisposition, and the methylation memory is transcriptionally SILENT (distinct from the residual immune infiltrate that stays expressed) -- a primed, clinically-invisible epigenetic state poised for same-site recurrence.


> **Biomarker hardened to 3 cohorts:** adding independent GSE115797 (24 lesional / 24 adjacent-normal skin), the scar-CpG classifier generalizes across all three methylation cohorts at **mean AUROC 0.845** (6 train/test pairs; GSE73894->GSE115797 0.970, GSE115797->GSE63315 0.976; weakest 0.589 when trained on the small UV cohort). The scar is a robust, transferable diagnostic methylation signature.

> **In-vitro causality (added):** in primary keratinocytes (GSE36287), the psoriasis cytokines IL-17A/TNF/IFN-gamma strongly induce the inflammatory program (+2.2 log2) but do NOT acutely silence the differentiation-memory genes (IL-17A median -0.10; GATA3/TBX/IRX unaffected; only CCL27/FOXC1 partially down). The silencing is therefore a CHRONIC EPIGENETIC process, not an acute cytokine response -- ruling out the simplest hypothesis and reinforcing the slow-methylation-remodeling memory model. Datasets acquired during the hunt: GSE115797 (3rd methylation cohort), GSE36287 (cytokine-stimulated keratinocytes).

> **FINAL out-of-platform replication (ARCHS4):** in the independent 58 GB ARCHS4 RNA-seq compendium (2,000 psoriasis vs 2,000 normal-skin samples, fully independent of the curated cohorts AND the microarray platform), the GATA-driven silencing replicates: 6/12 memory genes significantly silenced, led by **GATA3 (p=1.8e-6)** and **CCL27 (p=1.6e-3)** -- the same two that topped the curated meta-analysis. Effects attenuated by keyword-based heterogeneous sampling (honest), but direction + top genes hold. The mechanism is confirmed across curated microarray cohorts, single-cell, three methylation cohorts, AND an independent RNA-seq compendium.

> **AUDIT CORRECTION (added):** ARCHS4 out-of-platform replication is RETRACTED -- independent
> CPM-normalized analysis shows GATA3 up/null (p=0.42), not down; the committed result was a
> T-cell-composition / library-size artifact of keyword-based bulk sampling. The single-cell
> keratinocyte evidence (GATA3 down p~0, composition-controlled) is the valid confirmation. The
> cross-cohort biomarker (0.84-0.97) is non-circular and reproducible but optimistic vs a naive
> baseline (~0.67). Core silencing/persistence/enhancer-scar findings validated independently.
